  "prompt": "What is nerve cell?",
  "response": "A nerve cell, also known as a neuron, is a specialized cell that is fundamental to the functioning of the nervous system. Neurons are responsible for transmitting information throughout the body. They communicate through electrical signals (action potentials) and chemical signals (neurotransmitters). \n\nA typical neuron has three main parts:\n\n1. **Cell Body (Soma)**: This part contains the nucleus and other organelles necessary for the cell's metabolic activities. It integrates signals received from other neurons.\n\n2. **Dendrites**: These are branched extensions of the neuron that receive signals from other neurons. They play a crucial role in the neuron's ability to receive and process information.\n\n3. **Axon**: This is a long, thin projection that transmits electrical impulses away from the cell body to other neurons, muscles, or glands. The axon may be covered in a myelin sheath, which speeds up the transmission of signals.\n\nNeurons are classified into different types based on their function, including sensory neurons, motor neurons, and interneurons. Sensory neurons carry signals from sensory receptors to the central nervous system, motor neurons relay signals from the central nervous system to muscles and glands, and interneurons connect neurons within the central nervous system itself.\n\nOverall, neurons are essential for everything from reflex actions to complex cognitive functions like thinking and memory.",
